## Regression Modeling to Predict Numerical Values using XGBoost
This notebook shows how to predict numerical values using a multiple regression. Given demographic, purchase, and affinity card data for a set of customers, predict the number of years a customer remains at the same residence, as found in column YRS_RESIDENCE. Since YRS_RESIDENCE is a continuous variable, we will use the XGBoost algorithm. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database.

Examples of possible setting overrides for XGBoost

If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm

A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link:

– Algorithm Settings: XGBoost

– Switch between booster - gblinear, gbtree, dart

 By default the system uses the gbtree. The parameters are similar for gbtree and dart, but has more difference comparing to gblinear

v_setlst('booster') := 'gblinear';
v_setlst('booster') := 'gbtree';
v_setlst('booster') := 'dart';

– regularization parameters for all boosters

v_setlst('alpha')     := '0.1';
v_setlst('eta')       := '0.3';
v_setlst('lambda')    := '0.3';

– regularization parameters for tree based boosters: gbtree, dart

v_setlst('gamma')           := '0.1';
v_setlst('max_delta_step')  := '0.1';
v_setlst('max_depth')       := '6';
v_setlst('max_leaves')      := '10';
v_setlst('min_child_weight'):= '1';

– subsampling methods for tree based boosters: gbtree, dart

v_setlst('colsample_bylevel') := '1';
v_setlst('colsample_bynode')  := '1';
v_setlst('colsample_bytree')  := '1';

– Num of iteration rounds

v_setlst('num_round') := '100';

– For regression tasks, the default objective is reg:linear

v_setlst('objective') := 'reg:linear'

paragraphs.title: Apply XGBoost model to predict YRS_RESIDENCE with Prediction_Details
paragraphs.text:
%sql

-- Make predictions with upper and lower bounds and include explanatory prediction details
SELECT CUST_ID,
       round(PREDICTION_YRS_RES,3) PRED_YRS_RES,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute4",17,100)),'rank="4"/>') FOURTH_ATTRIBUTE
       FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
               PREDICTION(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *) PREDICTION_YRS_RES,
               PREDICTION_DETAILS(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *) PD
             FROM TEST_DATA_V
             WHERE CUST_ID < 100015
             ORDER BY CUST_ID) OUT,
             XMLTABLE('/Details'
                      PASSING OUT.PD
                      COLUMNS 
                      "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                      "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                      "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]',
                      "Attribute4" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[4]') 
       OUTPRED;

    round(PREDICTION(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *), 1) PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE,
    YRS_RESIDENCE ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE
  FROM TEST_DATA_V
  WHERE CUST_ID <= 100030
  ORDER BY CUST_ID;

paragraphs.title: Model quality statistics on the TEST data
paragraphs.text:
%sql

select ROUND(R2,6) COEF_OF_DETERMINATION_R2, 
       ROUND(MAE,6) MEAN_ABSOLUTE_ERROR, 
       ROUND(MSE,6) MEAN_SQUARED_ERROR, 
       ROUND(SQRT(MSE),6) ROOT_MEAN_SQUARED_ERROR
       FROM 
       (SELECT AVG(ABS(PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE - ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE)) MAE,
               AVG(POWER(PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE - ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE,2)) MSE,
               1-(SUM(POWER(ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE - PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE,2)))/(SUM(POWER(ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE - 
                 (SELECT AVG(ROUND(PREDICTION(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *), 1)) FROM TEST_DATA_V),2))) R2              
                 FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
                            ROUND(PREDICTION(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *), 1) PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE,
                            YRS_RESIDENCE ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE
                       FROM TEST_DATA_V))

paragraphs.title: Plot XGBoost model predictions vs actuals grouped by HOUSE_HOLD_SIZE
paragraphs.text:
%sql

-- Show predictions vs. actuals in a scatter plot grouped by HOUSE_HOLD_SIZE.  
-- Click the scatter plot icon and drag PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE to xAxis, 
--   ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE to yAxis and HOUSEHOLD_SIZE to group.
-- Clicking on the labels of each Household size, we can evaluate the model prediction 
--   quality for each different set

SELECT CUST_ID,
    round(PREDICTION(XGBOOST_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *), 1) PRED_YRS_RESIDENCE,
    YRS_RESIDENCE ACTUAL_YRS_RESIDENCE, CUST_GENDER, HOUSEHOLD_SIZE
  FROM TEST_DATA_V
  ORDER BY CUST_ID;

SELECT CUST_ID,
